  "prompt": "What is the probability that I will die at any given age?",
  "response": "The probability of dying at a specific age varies depending on numerous factors, including:\n\n1. Gender\n2. Country of residence\n3. Overall health\n4. Lifestyle choices\n5. Genetics\n6. Socioeconomic status\n\nTypically, mortality probability follows a \"bathtub curve\":\n- Very low in childhood and young adulthood\n- Gradually increasing in middle age\n- More rapidly increasing in older age\n\nLife expectancy and mortality tables provide detailed probabilities. In the US, for example:\n- Infant mortality: Around 0.5%\n- Age 25-34: About 0.1%\n- Age 45-54: Around 0.5%\n- Age 75-84: About 5-10%\n\nFor precise, personalized probabilities, consult:\n- Actuarial tables\n- Life insurance mortality calculators\n- Personal health assessments\n\nRemember, these are statistical probabilities based on population data, not individual predictions.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any part of this explanation?",
